Hi Neale,
Thanks for the review !
To answer your comments,

>> Fixing issues with TCP shouldn't be solved by adding work into the IP lookup fast path.
I updated the patch to add a new node (naming debatable) to not change the fast path.

>> I don't understand though the TCP issue you are trying to solve. A TCP connection should be able to >> accept packets from any of the devices interfaces. To TX does it route to the destination or send >> on the interface the socket is bound to?
If you happen to use the hoststack with per interface enabled features, 
you might want that a TCP connection accepted on an interface sends its replies as if they were coming from that same interface. Thus you need to know in ip-local which interface we end up on, to reply with the same sw_if_index. TX does route, but features are per source interface

Hope this helps

Cheers
-Nathan

> Patch Set 5:

> 
> Fixing issues with TCP shouldn't be solved by adding work into the IP lookup fast path.
> 

Unless the issue is in the IP lookup fast path :-)

> I don't understand though the TCP issue you are trying to solve. A TCP connection should be able to accept packets from any of the devices interfaces. To TX does it route to the destination or send on the interface the socket is bound to?

As Nathan already explained, the issue here is the marking of packets with the right rx interface. For instance, ignoring loopbacks for a second, if vpp has 2 "real" interfaces and interface A receives packets for interface B's IP address, everything above IP will see the packet as received on interface A, tcp included. TCP has no issues with that, but it will generate return packets with B's IP as source and marked as originated by A, because that's what it learned from IP when it accepted the connection. Similarly, the feature arc starting in ip-local won't work with interface B's features in this scenario. 

Same story holds for loopbacks, as the issue here is that the fib silently "switches" the interface on which the packet was received. That is, we can't figure out in ip-local if the packet was received by the interface in sw_if_index[VLIB_RX] or if the fib actually received the packet on another interface's receive dpo. 

So to solve this, we'd need something like the adj_index used by ip-rewrite, i.e., ip-local would need an index that could consistently be used to retrieve something that points to the actual interface that received the packet.

Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

s/buffers:/ip:/ in the Subject line of this patch....

Patch Set 7:

(3 comments)

> Patch Set 6:
> 
> (1 comment)
> 
> > Patch Set 6:
> > 
> > > Patch Set 6:
> > > 
> > > > Patch Set 6:
> > > > 
> > > > > Patch Set 5:
> > > > > 
> > > > > (2 comments)
> > > > > 
> > > > > Fixing issues with TCP shouldn't be solved by adding work into the IP lookup fast path.
> > > > > 
> > > > 
> > > > Unless the issue is in the IP lookup fast path :-)
> > > > 
> > > > > I don't understand though the TCP issue you are trying to solve. A TCP connection should be able to accept packets from any of the devices interfaces. To TX does it route to the destination or send on the interface the socket is bound to?
> > > > 
> > > > As Nathan already explained, the issue here is the marking of packets with the right rx interface. For instance, ignoring loopbacks for a second, if vpp has 2 "real" interfaces and interface A receives packets for interface B's IP address, everything above IP will see the packet as received on interface A, tcp included. TCP has no issues with that, but it will generate return packets with B's IP as source and marked as originated by A, because that's what it learned from IP when it accepted the connection. Similarly, the feature arc starting in ip-local won't work with interface B's features in this scenario. 
> > > 
> > > What does 'marked as originated by A' mean? setting (b)->sw_if_index[VLIB_RX]?
> > 
> > Exactly.
> 
> what affect does that have? in the TX path, isn't it largely ignored?
> 
> > If we want to also fix the ip-local feature arc (e.g., if packet for loopback IP, hand over to special node), we have to find the right sw_if_index in the head-of-arc node. As much as possible, I think, we'd like to avoid adding more nodes on path to host stack features (tunnels, tcp, udp)
> 
> defo no more nodes :)
> 
> i think in the current patch the use of the new rx_sw_if_index field and its use in the tcp input node keeps the scope of this change limited to TCP. but if we say that the arc chosen for local features is the loopback's, then this has wider ramifications.
> what local features would you expect to be applied when the user is expecting them to ultimately reach the host stack?

Hi,
Thanks for all the comments and proof-reading 😊
So I finallly did update the patch to cover the corner cases, using ~0 as a default value in 
ip[46]-receive, and covering this case in tcp_inlines.h

Tell me if I missed anything !

On the part of the discussion concerning indexing the local arc by rx_sw_if_index,
Florin & I spent a bit of time on https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/33432 trying to
see what breaks and what still works, but I'd argue it's a bit less of a priority.

Cheers
-Nathan
